definition.value: Anatomical entity that has no mass.
This begins with the newly hatched first-instar larva, through its maturation to the end of the last larval stage.
Anatomical entity that has mass.
Portion of tissue, that consists of one or more layers of epithelial cells connected to each other by cell junctions and which is underlain by a basal lamina.
An epithelium that is part of a midgut.

Anatomical structure that has as its parts two or more portions of tissue of at least two different types and which through specific morphogenetic processes forms a single distinct structural unit demarcated by bona-fide boundaries from other distinct structural units of different types.
Anatomical structure that is an individual member of a species and consists of more than one cell.
Organ consisting of a tissue made up of various elongated cells that are specialized to contract and thus to produce movement and mechanical work.
A multicellular structure that is a part of an organ.
A subdivision of an anatomical system.
An organ that is capable of transducing sensory stimulus to the nervous system.

value.value: Anatomical entity that comprises the organism in the early stages of growth and differentiation that are characterized by cleavage, the laying down of fundamental tissues, and the formation of primitive organs and organ systems. For example, for mammals, the process would begin with zygote formation and end with birth. For insects, the process would begin at zygote formation and end with larval hatching. For plant zygotic embryos, this would be from zygote formation to the end of seed dormancy. For plant vegetative embryos, this would be from the initial determination of the cell or group of cells to form an embryo until the point when the embryo becomes independent of the parent plant.

definition.value: Multicellular anatomical structure that consists of many cells of one or a few types, arranged in an extracellular matrix such that their long-range organisation is at least partly a repetition of their short-range organisation.
Anatomical structure that performs a specific function or group of functions
Any component associated with the anatomic structures in the head responsible for special sensations rather than general sensations, including the eyes, ears, nose, and tongue.
Any component associated with the organ for sight or vision.
A group of small, interconnected ganglia situated posterior to and between the two brain hemispheres and associated with the pharynx, esophagus and aorta.
A preoral neuromere or middle portion of insect brain wich represents fused ganglia of hypothetical antennal segment of head.
A segmental subdivision of the nervous system.
This terms is related to the development of nervous system, this mean, the neuromere could compose some ganglion in the nervous system of the adult.
The anterior part of the arthropod brain.
Commissure of the adult tritocerebrum, formed by the terminals of the fibers ascending through the cervical connective that extend to either half of the tritocerebrum.
Posterior division of insect brains, formed by ganglia of third segment of head.
The pair of closely united ventral longitudinal nerves with their segmental ganglia that is characteristic of many elongate invertebrates

value.value: Any subdivision of the hollow cylindrical anatomical structure.

definition.value: Any segmental subdivision of a nervous system. Includes metameric developmental segments, such as vertebrates neuromeres.
An anatomical structure that has more than one cell as a part.
A multicellular organism that existence_ends_with a post-juvenile adult stage and existence_starts_with a post-juvenile adult stage.
The transparent anterior portion of the fibrous coat of the eye that serves as the chief refractory structure

value.value: An endogenous molecular entity that results in a colour of an organism as the consequence of the selective absorption of light.

definition.value: Anatomical conduit that connects two adjacent body spaces (or a body space with the space surrounding the organism)
Orifice at the opposite end of an animal's digestive tract from the mouth.
Any hollow cylindrical anatomical structure containing a lumen through which substances are transported.
A muscular dilatation of the foregut in most mandibulate insects that is armed internally with chitinous teeth or plates for triturating food.
An exceretory tubule that usually opens to the exterior by a nephridiopore.
Skeletal subdivision that undergoes indirect development and includes elements that develop as a replacement or substitution of other elements or tissues.
A proximal-distal subdivision of the digestive tract.
A rigid covering that envelops an object.
Any one of the fibrous tracts of the peripheral nervous system, whether a single fiber or a group of fibers; a nerve trunk.
Surface structure that is a small, fleshy protuberance

Term no valid in Collembola
A subdivision of the gut along its long axis.
A sac that is an outpouching of a hollow (or a fluid-filled) structure in the body.
A wall, dividing a cavity or structure into smaller ones.
The anatomical structure which is part of the hemolymph vascular system and consists of a vascular wall and a vascular lumen.
The vessel which runs longitudinally in the dorsal midline of the body and may consist of anterior aorta, heart and posterior aorta.
The anatomical structure which is part of a pulsatile organ, and connects the lumen of the pulsatile organ with the surrounding hemocoel.
Anatomical structure which has as its parts one or more ordered aggregates of nucleotide, amino acid fatty acid or sugar molecules bonded to one another.

value.value: A class of hydrocarbons with an empirical formula of Cm(H20)n (where m and n may be equal) and includes monomers, polymers and derivatives of aldoses, ketoses, saccharides, and alditols.
A biomacromolecule consisting of large numbers of monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically. This term is commonly used only for those containing more than ten monosaccharide residues.
Long-chain polymer of N-acetylglucosamine, is a derivative of glucose.
